    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Arca obliquata</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_835",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Shell elongate-rectangular, wider at posterior end, giving an oblique outline (hence species and common name), lower margin concave. Outer surface brown, sculptured with fine radiating ridges and covered with velvety black ‘fur’ that is often eroded away except along margins. Eroded areas of shell become white.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_836",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Reaches 58 mm shell length.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_837",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Widespread across tropical Indian and Pacific Oceans, southwards to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> KwaZulu-Natal westwards to False Bay.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_838",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Usually found in small groups attached to underside of boulders in sandy pools, rock crevices, or among sponges. One of only a few species of this mainly tropical group that extend into cooler waters of the Western Cape. Details of biology unknown. The blood of Arc shells is unusual among bivalves in that it is red, due the presence of haemoglobin (possibly an adaptation to living in lower oxygen habitats under rocks?).</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_839",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>All bivalves feed by drawing water in then filtering it thought the enlarged sieve-like gills. Food particles filtered from the water are transported by cilia to the ventral edge of the gill and then forward to the mouth.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_840",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Details unknown, but almost all bivalves are broadcast spawners.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_841",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>Only two species of this characteristic and mostly tropical genus are found in the Western Cape, the other being the Sculptured ark shell <i>B. sculpturata</i>, which<i> </i>is smaller (up to 30 mm) and has less elongate, pink shell (central portion sometimes eroded to white) with a straight lower margin and yellow marginal fibers.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_842",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fourth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 148).<br><br>Kilburn, R & Rippey, E (1982). Sea Shells of Southern Africa. Macmillan South Africa, Johannesburg (p. 157).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_843",
